<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1554,2013]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1734,1760]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Morphology</emphasis>
. Small bivalve. Shell is rounded oval in outline shape and typically reaches 
<quantity box="[1203,1324,1734,1761]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="20.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="18.0">18–22 mm</quantity>
in length, 
<quantity box="[151,272,1770,1797]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="16.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="15.0">15–17 mm</quantity>
in height, and 
<quantity box="[440,561,1770,1797]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="11.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="10.0">10–13 mm</quantity>
in depth (more details in 
<bibRefCitation author="Welter-Schultes, F. W." box="[850,1100,1770,1796]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref60074" refString="Welter-Schultes, F. W. (2012) European non-marine molluscs, a guide for species identification, planet poster editions. Planet Poster Editions, Gottingen, 674 pp. [in German]" type="book" year="2012">Welter-Schultes, 2012</bibRefCitation>
, page 25, figure in the middle of the page).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1554,2013]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,1842,1868]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. Palearctic species common in the lowland regions of Central and Eastern Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Zhadin, V. I." box="[159,307,1878,1905]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref60565" refString="Zhadin, V. I. (1965) Mollusks of fresh and brackish waters of the USSR. Zoological Institute of the Academy of Sciences of the U. S. S. R., Moscow, 368 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1965">Zhadin 1965</bibRefCitation>
). It prefers fine substrate (silt, mud, sand) in larger slow–flowing rivers and canals, rarely it could be found in standing waters. In 
<collectingCountry box="[469,543,1914,1940]" name="Serbia" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Serbia</collectingCountry>
, it mostly inhabits large Pannonian/lowlands rivers (the Danube, Tisza and Sava Rivers).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1554,2013]" lastBlockId="36.[151,1436,150,249]" lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,380,1986,2012]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Other remarks</emphasis>
. One of the largest species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1777" box="[734,855,1986,2012]" class="Bivalvia" family="Sphaeriidae" genus="Sphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[734,855,1986,2012]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Sphaerium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1012,1087,1986,2012]" name="Serbia" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Serbia</collectingCountry>
. There are 10 nominal species known as synonyms (
<bibRefCitation author="Graf, D. L. &amp; Cummings, K. S." box="[396,679,150,176]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" refId="ref47315" refString="Graf, D. L. &amp; Cummings, K. S. (2021) The Freshwater Mussels (Unionoida) of the World (and other less consequential bivalves). Available from: http: // www. mussel-project. net / (accessed 20 March 2021)" type="url" year="2021">Graf &amp; Cummings 2021</bibRefCitation>
). On the IUCN Red List of threatened species it has been assessed as LC, yet with decreasing population trend, for Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="von Proschwitz, T. &amp; Killeen, I." box="[788,1147,186,212]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="4855418" refId="ref59884" refString="von Proschwitz, T. &amp; Killeen, I. (2011) Sphaerium rivicola. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2011, e. T 155853 A 4855418. [downloaded 4 May 2021]" type="journal article" year="2011">von Proschwitz &amp; Killeen 2011</bibRefCitation>
), and as VU on the global scale (
<bibRefCitation author="Van Damme, D." box="[221,439,222,249]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="8247251" refId="ref58648" refString="Van Damme, D. (2011 d) Sphaerium rivicola. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2011, e. T 18446 A 8247251. [down- loaded 16 March 2021] https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2011,2. RLTS. T 155853 A 4855157. en" type="journal article" year="2011">
Van Damme 2011 
<emphasis box="[425,439,222,248]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">d</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
